

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Real Facts & Fun";
}

<style>
    .full-bleed {
        margin-left: calc(-50vw + 50%);
        margin-right: calc(-50vw + 50%);
    }
</style>

<!-- PAGE HEADER -->
<div class="full-bleed" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #001a2d 0%, #000f1a 60%, #0f0f0f 100%);">
    <div class="container py-5 text-center">
        <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-2">Trivia & Surprises</p>
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold text-white mb-3">Real Facts &amp; Fun</h1>
        <p class="text-white-50 mx-auto" style="max-width:560px;">
            The behind-the-scenes stories, wild coincidences, and little-known truths that
            make cinema even more extraordinary than what ends up on screen.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- FACT OF THE WEEK -->
<div class="py-5">
    <div class="card bg-dark border-warning rounded-4 p-4 p-lg-5 text-white text-center">
        <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-2">🏆 Fact of the Week</p>
        <div class="display-1 mb-3">🦖</div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold text-white mb-3">The T-Rex Didn't Sound Like a T-Rex</h3>
        <p class="text-white-50 lh-lg mx-auto" style="max-width:620px;">
            The iconic roar of the T-Rex in <strong class="text-white">Jurassic Park (1993)</strong>
            was created by mixing the sounds of a baby elephant's sneeze, a tiger's growl,
            and an alligator's gurgle. Sound designer Gary Rydstrom recorded the elephant at
            a wildlife sanctuary after it sneezed unexpectedly — and knew immediately he had something special.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-3">
            <span class="badge bg-dark border border-warning text-warning">Sound Design</span>
            <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary ms-2">Jurassic Park · 1993</span>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- FACTS GRID -->
<div class="full-bleed bg-black py-5">
    <div class="container py-2">
        <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-1">The Collection</p>
        <h2 class="display-5 fw-bold text-white mb-4">Mind-Bending Facts</h2>

        <div class="row g-4">

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🎨</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Production Design</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">Mad Max: Fury Road took 15 years to make</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        George Miller spent 15 years developing <em>Fury Road</em>. The film used roughly
                        80% practical effects — nearly everything you see on screen was really there, really moving,
                        and really exploding. The storyboard alone was 3,500 panels long.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🎭</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Acting</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">Heath Ledger locked himself in a hotel room for a month</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        To prepare for the Joker in <em>The Dark Knight</em>, Ledger isolated himself
                        for six weeks, keeping a diary written in character. He developed the Joker's voice,
                        mannerisms, and psychology entirely alone before a single day of filming.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🎬</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Directing</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">Stanley Kubrick shot 127 takes of a single scene</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        For <em>The Shining</em>, Kubrick made Shelley Duvall film the baseball bat scene
                        over 127 takes — a Guinness World Record. Duvall's exhaustion and distress were real,
                        which Kubrick believed made the performance more authentic.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">💰</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Box Office</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">Paranormal Activity cost $15,000 and made $193 million</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        Shot over seven days in director Oren Peli's own house,
                        <em>Paranormal Activity</em> became one of the most profitable films ever made
                        relative to budget. It grossed over 12,800 times its production cost worldwide.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🌊</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Practical FX</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">Titanic's water was only waist-deep in most shots</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        Many of <em>Titanic's</em> flooding scenes were filmed in a tank of only
                        waist-height water. Creative camera angles and forced perspective made it look
                        like actors were swimming in fathoms of icy ocean. The cast still complained
                        it was freezing cold.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🤝</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Improvisation</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">"Here's looking at you, kid" was improvised</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        Humphrey Bogart's iconic line in <em>Casablanca</em> was not in the script.
                        It was something Bogart reportedly said to Ingrid Bergman between takes
                        during filming — she later said it was one of her favourite lines in cinema.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🎵</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Score</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">John Williams wrote Jaws' theme in two notes</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        Spielberg laughed when Williams played him the two-note motif for <em>Jaws</em>,
                        thinking it was a joke. Williams insisted it was the theme. That alternating
                        E and F became one of the most recognisable pieces of film music ever written.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">🧊</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Behind the Scenes</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">The actors in The Shining really didn't like each other</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        Kubrick intentionally kept Jack Nicholson and Shelley Duvall from bonding on set.
                        He encouraged the crew to side with Nicholson and treated Duvall harshly —
                        all to manufacture the real tension between their characters.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="fs-2 mb-3">📽️</div>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary mb-2">Film History</span>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold text-warning mb-2">The first film audiences ran from a train</h6>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-0">
                        When the Lumière Brothers screened <em>L'Arrivée d'un train en gare de La Ciotat</em>
                        in 1896 — a 50-second clip of a train arriving at a station —
                        audience members reportedly fled in terror, believing the train was real
                        and heading straight for them.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</div>

